{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_janeway_ver01/data/sn87055779/00416150874/1930092401/0090.xml":{"full_text":"OFFICIALS AGREE\nDEPRESSION NEAR\nEND; SEE UPTURN\nCommerce Head Makes\nI Statement; Fess Com\nments.\nBr tnlt.d Pr..\u00bb:\nWASHINGTON. Sept. 23.\u2014Agree- j\nmerit that the bottom of the deprts-1\nsion has been reached and business is\nnow on the upgrade was given Mon\nday in statements by Secretary of\nCommerce Robert P. lAmont and\nChairman Simeon Fess of the Repub\nllcan national committee.\nMonday night editors of trade Jour- j\nnals predicted favorable develop-\nments in agriculture, residential;\nbuilding and the automobile industry,\nin radio speeches.\n\"Business,\u201d Lamont said, \u201chas\nceased the market decline character-\nistic of a number of earlier months i\nand there are some distinctly encour- i\naging features.\u201d j\nFess, who expressed concern over j\nthe political and economic unrest1\nmanifest in various parts of the;\nworld, said he thought America has\nturned the comer and is now on the\nway back to normal.\n\u2022V\nCites Trade Growth.\nLamont singled out as the most\nencouraging aspects the growth oi\nip\\: export trade as shown ip August sta\nj tistics. and the \u201cdistinct picking up\nof retail trade in this country.\u2019'\nPrecise statistics are not available\non retail trade, but\u2019preliminary fig\nures. he said, indicate improvement.\nV and \u201cthis is more than confirmed by\nthe statements of many representa\ntives not only of department stores\nbut of other classes of retail stores.\u201d\nThe tiade journal editors, holding\nfv a national conference here, called at\nthe White House and various bust\ni ness bureaus cf the government,\niff Various ones reported on the indus\nyx tries they represented in their radio\n\u2022y speeches.\nNorman G. Shidle said the_ last\nthree months of the year would show\nup more favorably in comparison\nwith the 1929 record, with a total out\nput about 15 per cent less. The year\u2019s\ntotals will run 40 per cent under 1929.\nIre said. The year has been a poor\none. but \u201cthe immediate outlook is\nfavorable and the long swing ouUool:\nextremely bright.\u201d he added.\nStimulate Building.\nPaul L. Aldrich said fanners have\nmade sacrifices in their incomes so\nthat the country might be led. and\nthat \u201ceven for the industrially unem\nployed palatable and nutiitious food\nis available.\u201d\nThomas S. Holden said the record\nbreaking volume of public works con\nstruction has kept business from a\nworse decline, and advocated stimu\nlation of residential building as es\nsential to a business revival. Resi\ndential contracts have been ,60 per\ncent under the bconi period rate, he\nsaid. Such contracts arc somewhat\ngreater this month than in August,\nhe said.\nPaul Wooton said \u201cmuch has been\ndone to cushion the effect of the de\npression\u201d under the President\u2019s lead\ner- ership, and that the effects cf this\nyear's slump are not as disastrous as\nthat of 1921.\nWallace Thompson said prospects\nfor a foreign trade revival were ex\ncellcnt ;that tariffs seem to be rising\nto a point where they almost balance\none another. \u201cThese are barriers to\ntrade, and will always tc, and our\ns .own recent tariff is actually more\ndangerous as an cram pie than as an\nactual achievement.\"\nBREATHED THROUGH GLASS\nPOUGHKEEPSIE. N. Y.-The man\nwho breathed through a glass tube\n10 years is dead. Hugh Kennan. whose\nwindpipe was removed and a glass\ntube substituted, died after a short\nillness. v\nHOSIERY HOSIERY\nWEDNESDAY SALE\n1200 pairs women\u2019s first quality,\nfull-fashiored $1.50 silk hose. Wed\nnesday only, see window. 09c.\nBRANDON-DURRELL CO.\nAdv.\u201423tl\nMAN-, HELD AS ALIEN,\nASKS FOR FREEDOM\nBy Culled Pw**t\nSAN FRANCISCO, Sept. 23.\u2014A\n\u201cman without a country\u201d appealed to\nFederal Judge A. F. St. Sure Monday\nto be freed from Angel island before\nwinter so that he might obtain em\nployment.\nGeorge Montgomery, 50, wrote a\nletter to,the judge, stating that he\nhad been held in Angel island by im\nmigration officials for nine months\nand said he was \u201cgetting tired of It.\u201d\nHe maintained be is an American\ncitizen because his father was\nnaturalized 40 years ago, but that im\nmigration officials have been unable\nto find the papers.\nMOVER SOVIET\nSTARVATION PLOT\nCounter Revolutionists\nFound by Secret Po\nlice Force.\nl\nBjr I'nlted Press:\nMOSCOW, Sept. 23.\u2014Discovery oil\nan extensive counter-revolutionary\nand espionage organization aiming at j\noverthrow of the Soviet government\nby disorganization of food supplies\nwas announced Monday by Soviet\nsecret police.\n\u201cThe Soviet power will be merciless\nwith these organizers who planned to\ncause starvation throughout the\nSoviet union and who are the agents\nof capitalists.\u201d the communist news\npaper Pravda said.\nThe secret police charge that a\nBritish firm. The Union Cold Storage\nCo., paid the revolutionary leaders\nalmost 1,000.000 gold rubles In six\nyeais of activity. The organization\nwas formed in 1924 when the storage\ncompany\u2019s representative named\nFotherhill\u2014came here in an effort to\nobtain a concession to build cold stor\nage plants.\nAbout 50 person were arrested in\nconnection with the plot, which\nsecret police indicated was one of the\nmost serious discovered in recent\nyean.\nTRAIN HITS AUTO;\nFOUR TEXANS DIE\n-voinan. Three Children\nKilled Fourth Hurt\nCritically.\nBy l nltcd l'rpN\u00bb:\nEASTLAND, Texas. Sept. 23.\u2014One\nwoman and three children were killed\nnear here late Monday when a Taxes\nPacific passenger train struck the:'\nautomobile.\nThe dead, all of Eastland, are:\nMRS. E. W. HALBERT. 30.\nMARY LOUISE MITCHELL, 6.\nCLIFTON HALBERT, 11. t\nELBERT HALBERT, 9.\nJ. W. Mitchell, jr\u201e 9, was injured\nhospital attaches Monday night said\nids condition was critical.\nMrs. Halbert was driving her sons\nand the Mitchell children home from\nschool when the locomotive struck\ntheir car. Their bodies were-dragged\n73 feet along the right-of-way. The\nmachine was demolished.\nOil tanks, standing on a spare track\nnear the scene of the tragedy, were\n.relieved to have obscured Mrs. Hai\noert's vision.\nI COUPLE DIE ON SAME DAY\nBARRINGTON. 111.\u2014Friends from\nchildhood and married when only 18\nyears old, Mr.' and Mrs. William\nrdooer emigrated from Ireland and\nj lived here for 48 years without being\nseparated at any time. Both were\ntaken 111 the same week and died on\nthe same day within a few hours of\neach other. Neither of them ever\n.col; a vacation without the other.\nred Mr. Mooer refused to Join any\nj Paternal organisation because his\nwife could not become a 1 fiiember\nwith him.\nk;'S\n\n*--c\nr\nMrs,\nWear\nDear Madam:\nIn years past it was impossible to resole a woman\u2019s shoe\narid leave 'comfort, beauty and style which the women de\nmand.\nS\nBut since the newly Invented sole fastener machine came\non the market which I have recently installed in conjunc\ntion with my modern maehine\u2019-y. it enables me to lenew\nworn shoes in such a manner .hat will be pleasing to you\nat a much smaller cost than buying a new pair.\nCall us or bring in your discarded shoes and have us\nprove the above. Yours Sincerely,\n!\",!X SHOE HOif*!\u2122.\n109 W. JEFFERSON EL*\nA Few Doors Off Michigan S.\nSuits Sconged and Pressed 3SC\nHats Cleaned and Blocked (Ladies and Mena)\u2019 50c\nm\nv*\ni\n\n\nS*\nm\nCIVIC HOUSING CAMPAIGN\nFor the Notre Dame Football Season\n(Sponsored by the N. D. Club of the St. Joseph Valley)'\nGentlemen:\np>\n\n\n\n\n\n\nI have. .Single Room(s) $....per night\n1 navo. .Double Room (t) .per night\nwhich 1 will rent to persons you recommend during- the\nfootball season if these rooms are not previously occupied.\nau\ns\nv\n\n\n3fef\nv\niy..\"\nMAIL TO\nJWn Dame Oak\nat Mm\nH Joseph Talk;\nSIS Oliver Betel\nSoath Bead. lad.\nName\nw:\n..\u2022V i>\nAddress\nTd. No.\n\ng\u00a7;\nf